On 09/07/05, Michael &lt;mkoss917@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; 
&gt;  Hi. I was brainstorming and idea on the drive home from work tonight
&gt; and realized I didn&#39;t know how to test something. This didn&#39;t come as
&gt; a major shock, but I think I have an idea for a solution and I would
&gt; like some devil&#39;s advocates :)
&gt; 
&gt; Suppose the following class:
&gt; 
&gt; public class SomeClass {
&gt; public boolean doSomething(double x, double y) {
&gt; double a = Math.random();
&gt; double b = Math.random();
&gt; return (x+a) &gt; (y+b);
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Writing a test case for this is next to impossible because you do not
&gt; know the results of the method beforehand. But what if there were an
&gt; interface:
&gt; 
&gt; public interface DoubleGenerator { public double nextDouble(); }
&gt; 
&gt; that SomeClass depends on.
&gt; 
&gt; public class SomeClass {
&gt; private DoubleGenerator doubleGenerator;
&gt; //setter method
&gt; 
&gt; public boolean doSomething(double x, double y) {
&gt; double a = doubleGenerator.nextDouble();
&gt; double b = doubleGenerator.nextDouble();
&gt; return (x+a) &gt; (y+b);
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; The implementation of DoubleGenerator in production code could be a
&gt; wrapper around Math.random() and a testing implementation could allow
&gt; you to set the sequence of doubles to return.
&gt; 
&gt; You could also use java.util.Random instead of DoubleGenerator and
&gt; subclass it to allow setting of the sequence, but I don&#39;t like having
&gt; all the extra methods when SomeClass only needs one of them. However,
&gt; having the extra methods allows for flexibility later. Opinions?
&gt; 
&gt; Also, is setting a DoubleGenerator with two doubles good practice? For
&gt; now, doSomething() needs two doubles, but it may need three or four
&gt; later. Is this &quot;inside knowledge&quot; bad practice when writing tests?
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks for your opinions.
&gt; 
&gt; Michael.
&gt; 
&gt; You should remove part of the &#39;inside knowledge&#39; aspect by passing the 
DoubleGenerator in as a parameter, to the method or to the constructor, so 
that the inside knowledge part becomes public. Otherwise it all seems 
reasonable enough.

James


